Ms. Thompson's statement can be transformed into a logical implication:
$$ P \implies Q $$
where $ P $ is "a student answered all the essay questions correctly" and $ Q $ is "the student passed the course."

The contrapositive of this statement is:
$$ \neg Q \implies \neg P $$
which translates to "If a student did not pass the course, then the student did not answer all the essay questions correctly."

Now, evaluating each answer choice given:
$\textbf{(A)}\ \text{ Incorrect. Not passing does not imply answering all questions incorrectly.}
$\textbf{(B)}\ \text{ Correct. It's equivalent to the contrapositive $\neg Q \implies \neg P$.}
$\textbf{(C)}\ \text{ Incorrect. This is the converse, which isn't necessarily true.}
$\textbf{(D)}\ \text{ Incorrect. Original statement does not assure that passing is only via answering all questions correctly.}
$\textbf{(E)}\ \text{ Incorrect. Passing could theoretically occur without any essay questions being correct, if there were none or other criteria were used.}

Given this analysis, the correct choice is:
$$ \textbf{(B)} $$
The final answer is $\boxed{\textbf{(B)}}$
